      <hedline>
        <hl1>Repellent Insect</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>George Dale letter on Derek Bickerton's June 4 review of Gilbert Waldbauer's book Millions of Monarchs, Bunches of Beetles calls depredations by Anopheles mosquito, vector for malaria, more onerous than locusts and grasshoppers</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Derek Bickerton's review of Gilbert Waldbauer's fine book ''Millions of Monarchs, Bunches of Beetles'' (June 4) includes the statement ''Locusts and other types of grasshopper have impinged on our species more onerously than any other insect, barring only plague-bearing lice.'' The plague vector is in fact the rat flea, but surely the depredations of the Anopheles mosquito, vector for malaria, qualify as even more onerous. Malaria is estimated to be responsible for half of all the deaths in human history caused by infectious diseases.</p>
        <p>George Dale  Armonk, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
